articles.title: Waymos new Zeekr robotaxi seen testing in San Diego
articles.body: STORY San Diego, California November 19, 2025 Waymos new Zeekr robotaxi is spotted testing in San Diego before services start in the city next year The vehicle developed with Chinese automaker Geely is part of Waymos expansion to Las Vegas, San Diego and DetroitWaymo announced in early November it will launch its robotaxi service in Las Vegas, San Diego and Detroit next year, marking its biggest geographic expansion yet.The Alphabet unit will also start driving its new Zeekr-built vehicles, alongside its existing Jaguar I-PACE fleet, it added.The new Zeekr model, developed with Chinese automaker Geely, are designed specifically for robotaxi use cases and will be rolled out gradually as the company expands its service.Companies like Waymo, Tesla TSLA.O and Amazons Zoox are investing billions into self-driving technology.Tesla launched its long-awaited robotaxi service earlier this year, while Waymo already operates driverless services in Phoenix, San Francisco, Los Angeles, and Austin, and has completed more than 10 million trips.

articles.body: Peter Thiels hedge fund Thiel Macro sold around 76 percent of its stake in Tesla during the third quarter, according to the 13F filing, as the billionaire decided to reduce his holdings in fellow PayPal Mafia-member Elon Musks EV giant amid possible AI bubble risks. Thiel Macro sold 207,613 TSLA shares in third quarter, cutting its Tesla position by about 76 percent. After those sales, Thiels fund holds 65,000 shares of Tesla, which remain its largest investment, valued at $28.91 million and representing 38.83 percent of the portfolio.

articles.title: Waymos new Zeekr robotaxi seen testing in San Diego
articles.body: STORY San Diego, California November 19, 2025 Waymos new Zeekr robotaxi is spotted testing in San Diego before services start in the city next year The vehicle developed with Chinese automaker Geely is part of Waymos expansion to Las Vegas, San Diego and DetroitWaymo announced in early November it will launch its robotaxi service in Las Vegas, San Diego and Detroit next year, marking its biggest geographic expansion yet.The Alphabet unit will also start driving its new Zeekr-built vehicles, alongside its existing Jaguar I-PACE fleet, it added.The new Zeekr model, developed with Chinese automaker Geely, are designed specifically for robotaxi use cases and will be rolled out gradually as the company expands its service.Companies like Waymo, Tesla TSLA.O and Amazons Zoox are investing billions into self-driving technology.Tesla launched its long-awaited robotaxi service earlier this year, while Waymo already operates driverless services in Phoenix, San Francisco, Los Angeles, and Austin, and has completed more than 10 million trips.
